text:
Many moons have passed, since the gremlins went to war.

Onwards and upwards, bigger weapons than before.

Gura took cover, she shivered on patrol.

The arms race crazy, simply way out of control.

Then her friend threw it, the latest device.

Gura went and got it, following chat's advice.

Her hoodie split, and her energy lost.

How many more will this dreaded war cost?

Then came the lag, and the stream running s***.

If the bugs didn't get you, you'd probably quit.

But the gremlins battled on, through hunger and back pain.

Living to fight, just to mess up again.

And now it's the curtain call, the final onslaught.

No better classic could you possibly have bought.

But spare a thought for Gura and with it her friend.

So shrimp for their honour, and shrimp until the end.

author: @lucas_187

text:
Great stream! A bit tricky to start off without prior experience, as Worms is very confusing for new players, especially with all the new stuff they added in the latest game.

If you do plan on bringing other Holomems into it, I would recommend going through the ingame tutorials/first few missions to get the hang of it, many game mechanics are specific to the Worms series and not found anywhere else.

Also, it would be great to have a basic bootcamp session (off-stream if needed) ran by Ame (or anyone in Hololive with Worms experience):

(a) Explaining and testing the basic movements: moving left/right, the different jumps to move around the map (simple jump, double-jump), fall damage.

(b) Explaining the concept of Turns:
- the Movement phase (before a weapon is used) allows unlimited movements (within the turn timer)
- tools do not count as weapons (nb: girder building is considered a weapon ; the rope or jetpacks are considered tools)
- after using a weapon you can still move for a few seconds to relocate to a safer location (default setting is 3 or 5 seconds)
- if the controlled Worm takes any damage (fall damage, mine, sentry, etc) at any moment, the turn ends

(c) Explaining the concept of dangerous ledges:
- when a Worm enters a body of water, it instantly dies, no matter how many health point it has left
- many weapons (like the baseball bat) are specialized in dealing a lot of knockback on the target, instead of raw damage, to push the targeted Worm into the sea
- therefore, any Worm standing on the edge (of the crater...) of any structure is at high risk of being pushed away into the sea

(d) Explaining the items and crafting system:
- items (wooden crates, toolboxes, first aid box) falling from the sky can be picked up during the Movement phase by simply walking over them
- toolboxes contain tools and powerups (double damage for example)
- wooden crates either contain extra weapons, or ingredients for crafting
- crafting is done using ingredients, obtained in crates or by dismantling other weapons

I would also recommend ticking off a lot more weapons/tools for the first few games: when new players are offered 30+ items to choose from and a time-limited turn, it is excessively confusing and doesn't leave them enough time to familiarize with the various items.

Speaking of which, the first 2-3 games should definitely have the maximum turn time (90 seconds), to let the newcomers navigate the weapons menu and ask about the various items. It might slow down the pace a bit at first, thus why it might be better to do it off-stream, but it is very useful for new players, who otherwise might bounce off the Worms series before getting the hang of it. Note that having it set to 90 seconds doesn't mean every turn will be this long, it only means it can go for as long as 90 seconds before forcibly ending.

Once the basics are done, the funniest part can start right away: crazier, deadlier weapons and (attempted) tricks using jetpacks and ropes. We could already see it happening a bit on this stream, so the Training Arc Episode isn't that long: after an hour a new player can start having fun and climb the learning curve steadily.
